  "prompt": "What are the best small classes for freshmen at Western Carolina University?",
  "response": "Selecting the best small classes at Western Carolina University (WCU) for freshmen can depend on your interests and major, but here are a few types of classes that are typically appreciated by freshmen for their size and engagement:\n\n1. **Freshman Seminar (USI 101)** \u2013 These seminars are designed to introduce first-year students to the university experience. They usually cover a variety of topics depending on the instructor and provide an intimate setting to engage with peers and professors.\n\n2. **Honors College Courses** \u2013 If you're part of the Honors College, you'll have access to smaller, discussion-based classes across a range of subjects. These classes often provide a more rigorous and engaging academic environment.\n\n3. **Introductory Writing Courses (ENGL 101/202)** \u2013 While these might not be small by design, they often feature more personal interaction due to the nature of writing instruction and peer reviews.\n\n4. **Intro to Psychology (PSY 150)** \u2013 Psychology is a popular subject among freshmen, and introductory courses tend to offer engaging content in a smaller setting, especially if there are multiple sections.\n\n5. **Art and Music Appreciation Classes** \u2013 Courses like ART 104 (Art Appreciation) or MUS 101 (Music Appreciation) can be both educational and enjoyable, with opportunities for interaction and personal expression.\n\n6. **Language Courses** \u2013 If you're interested in learning a new language or advancing in one you've already studied, language courses are generally smaller and offer lots of opportunities for participation and practice.\n\n7. **Special Topics Courses** \u2013 Keep an eye out for any special topics courses offered in the departments that interest you. These are often designed to be smaller and more focused on specific interests of students and faculty.\n\nWhen choosing classes, consider your interests and academic goals, and consult with your academic advisor to find the best options. Engaging professors and interactive class formats can make a significant difference in your first-year experience.",
